Say you=C2=A0are a big mutual fund and you own 1,000 shares of Stock X and =
you want to sell. You meet a pension fund that wants to buy 1,000 shares of=
 Stock X, the pension fund comes to your office to=C2=A0negotiate a trade, =
and you agree on a price of, say, $14 per share. The pension fund reaches i=
nto its bag of cash, pulls out $14,000 in crisp $20 bills and hands them to=
 you. You open up your vault, pull out a stock certificate that says =E2=80=
=9C1,000 Shares of Stock X=E2=80=9D and hand it to the pension fund. =E2=80=
=9CPleasure doing business with you,=E2=80=9D you say; you shake hands with=
 the pension fund and it walks out of your office holding the shares.
This is not quite an accurate description of how you=C2=A0trade stocks in 2=
024. For instance, in reality,=C2=A0you negotiate this trade anonymously an=
d electronically on the stock exchange,
  [1]
 the =E2=80=9Cstock=E2=80=9D consists of an entry in an electronic database=
 rather than paper certificates, and the =E2=80=9C$14,000=E2=80=9D consists=
 of an entry in a different electronic database. But those distinctions are=
 not particularly important, and let=E2=80=99s ignore them for now.
Instead let=E2=80=99s just pretend that everything is done face to face wit=
