=E2=80=99s a tendency to leak information into prices slowly,=E2=80=9D says=
=C2=A0Peter Hecht, managing director at US investment firm=C2=A0AQR Capital=
 Management. =E2=80=9CIt dampens volatility, giving this false perception o=
f low risk.=E2=80=9D

By the way, in addition to being pleasant for the investors, there is=C2=A0=
some=C2=A0argument that it is socially useful for=C2=A0lenders=C2=A0not to =
know what their loans are worth. We   talked the other day about competitio=
n between private credit and bank lending, and part of the story there is t=
hat banks =E2=80=9Cwere saddled with billions of dollars of losses on the d=
eals they agreed to finance in 2022,=E2=80=9D which =E2=80=9Climited [their=
] interest in extending new loans=E2=80=9D for a while. The public syndicat=
ed loan market is a fairly mark-to-market world these days,
  [4]
=C2=A0which makes it vulnerable to market cycles: If you make some loans, a=
nd then the market price of loans goes down, you have a big mark-to-market =
loss on your loans, which means that no one is going to let you deploy capi=
tal into new loans =E2=80=94=C2=A0even though, because=C2=A0the price of lo=
ans has gone down, you should be able to get good deals on new loans. If yo=
u can just blithely ignore mark-to-market losses, then you can keep making =
loans through the cycle.
Or that Bloomberg story cites payment-in-kind loans, =E2=80=9Cwhere a compa=
ny chooses to defer interest payments to its direct lender and promises to =
make up for it in its final loan settlement=E2=80=9D:

This option of kicking the can down the road is often used by lower-rated b=
orrowers and while it doesn=E2=80=99t necessarily signal distress, it does =
cause anxiety about what it might be obscuring. ...
And yet the value of loans even after these deals is strikingly generous. A=
ccording to Solve, about three-quarters of PIK loans were valued at more th=
an 95 cents on the dollar at the end of September. =E2=80=9CThis raises que=
stions about how portfolio companies struggling with interest servicing are=
 valued so high,=E2=80=9D says Eugene Grinberg, the fintech=E2=80=99s cofou=
nder.

True. But a lender who=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t have to mark down its loans=C2=
=A0is more likely to=C2=A0let a borrower defer interest payments, which is =
nice for a borrower that runs into trouble. Lenders have more flexibility t=
o work cooperatively with borrowers if they are not subject to market disci=
pline. That is not obviously good =E2=80=94=C2=A0it can lead to  zombie com=
panies, misallocation of resources, etc. =E2=80=94 but it has some advantag=
es.

 =20
   =20
      Elsewhere in overly informative public markets
   =20
 =20

I   sometimes=C2=A0  like to   argue that the stock market should be open 1=
5 or 30 minutes a day: Everyone could form their views about valuation at t=
heir leisure and then meet up,=C2=A0briefly, to trade stocks. The advantage=
 of this is that a 15-minute trading session would not=C2=A0be vastly less =
informative than a 6.5-hour trading session, and would give traders more ti=
me with their families. The disadvantage is that sometimes you need to sell=
 some stuff quickly to raise money or buy some other stuff, and you can=E2=
=80=99t necessarily wait until noon the next day. (See the first section ab=
ove!)
Realistically, though, the trend is probably the other way, and people   wa=
nt to trade all night and on weekends. And so on Tuesday, 24X National Exch=
ange LLC  filed an application with the US Securities and Exchange Commissi=
on to become a national securities exchange and run around the clock, more =
or less. (=E2=80=9CThe Exchange will pause trading every day between 7:00 p=
.m. ET and 8:00 p.m. ET,=E2=80=9D  says its user manual, and also =E2=80=9C=
each Saturday from 8 a.m. ET until 11 a.m. ET,=E2=80=9D but still that=E2=
=80=99s a lot of trading.) We have   talked about 24X Exchange before, in 2=
021, when it previously =E2=80=9Cfiled key parts of its application,=E2=80=
=9D and I guess it=E2=80=99s still doing that.=C2=A0

