       =20
  [1] Which, to be clear, is a computer. You don't like go to the floor of =
the New York Stock Exchange.


  [2] More normally, the hedge fund posted cash collateral with you, the ca=
sh collateral earns interest, and you rebate some of the interest to the he=
dge fund and keep some of it (the lending fee) for yourself. Though in hard=
-to-borrow stocks there can be a =E2=80=9Cnegative rebate,=E2=80=9D i.e. yo=
u keep all the interest and the hedge fund pays you some extra. Also in rea=
lity all of this will probably be done through brokers=E2=80=99 stock lendi=
ng platforms rather than face-to-face, but I am trying to keep the old-time=
y quaintness in the text.


  [3] In this parenthesis I am using the word =E2=80=9Ccash=E2=80=9D in its=
 brokerage-account sense, meaning =E2=80=9Cnot margin.=E2=80=9D If you own =
stock in a margin account at a retail brokerage, your *broker* has probably=
 loaned it out to a short seller and has to go find it for you.


  [4] This was not particularly true historically: It used to be that bank =
loans were made by banks, which could hold them on their books until maturi=
ty and=20
not mark them down for temporary market fluctuations. That is, it used to b=
e that =E2=80=9Cprivate lending=E2=80=9D was largely done by banks. That=20
has changed. But banks used to argue that this was good, that their relativ=
e insulation from market prices made them better long-term partners for the=
ir borrowers than flighty bond markets.


