<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Say you=C2=A0are a big mutual fund and you own=
 1,000 shares of Stock X and you want to sell. You meet a pension fund that=
 wants to buy 1,000 shares of Stock X, the pension fund comes to your offic=
e to=C2=A0negotiate a trade, and you agree on a price of, say, $14 per shar=
e. The pension fund reaches into its bag of cash, pulls out $14,000 in cris=
p $20 bills and hands them to you. You open up your vault, pull out a stock=
 certificate that says =E2=80=9C1,000 Shares of Stock X=E2=80=9D and hand i=
t to the pension fund. =E2=80=9CPleasure doing business with you,=E2=80=9D =
you say; you shake hands with the pension fund and it walks out of your off=
ice holding the shares.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is not quite an accurate description of h=
ow you=C2=A0trade stocks in 2024. For instance, in reality,=C2=A0you negoti=
ate this trade anonymously and electronically on the stock exchange,<a clas=
s=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-dec=
oration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #0=
00000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent =
!important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a> the =E2=80=9Cstock=E2=80=9D consists of an entry in an electronic data=
base rather than paper certificates, and the =E2=80=9C$14,000=E2=80=9D cons=
ists of an entry in a different electronic database. But those distinctions=
 are not particularly important, and let=E2=80=99s ignore them for now.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Instead let=E2=80=99s just pretend that everyt=
hing is done face to face with=C2=A0vaults and paper money, and talk about =
a different complication. That complication is: If you are a big mutual fun=
d in 2024 and you own 1,000 shares of Stock X, you don=E2=80=99t just keep =
the shares in your vault. No, what has actually happened is that, a month a=
go, a hedge fund came to you and said: =E2=80=9CHey, I hear you have some s=
hares of Stock X sitting in your vault. I would like to borrow those shares=
 from you, for my own purposes.=E2=80=9D And you sat down with that hedge f=
und and negotiated a trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0not a stock trade, but a stock=C2=
=A0<em>lending=C2=A0</em>trade. You didn=E2=80=99t sell your stock, but you=
 agreed to lend the hedge fund your stock certificates, and the hedge fund =
agreed to post some cash collateral to secure the loan, and the hedge fund =
agreed to pay you a fee =E2=80=94=C2=A0essentially, interest =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0for borrowing the stock.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-2"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !importa=
nt; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Also the loan has a term: Maybe you agreed that the hedge fund wo=
uld return the stock certificates in 90 days, for instance, but much more l=
ikely you agreed to =E2=80=9Copen=E2=80=9D term, where the hedge fund can r=
eturn the shares to you whenever it wants, and you can demand them back whe=
never you want.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why did the hedge fund want to borrow your sto=
ck? There=E2=80=99s really only one possible answer: The hedge fund wanted =
to=C2=A0<em>short=C2=A0</em>Stock X; it wanted to sell shares of Stock X th=
at it didn=E2=80=99t own, betting that the stock would drop and=C2=A0it cou=
ld buy the shares back cheaper later. To do that, of course, it needed shar=
es of Stock X: In my slightly fanciful=C2=A0world of tangible face-to-face =
stock trades, a hedge fund can=E2=80=99t =E2=80=9Csell Stock X=E2=80=9D wit=
hout handing over actual certificates of Stock X. This is where you came in=
: You loaned the hedge fund some shares of Stock X, the hedge fund sold=C2=
=A0them, and it hopes to buy them back in the future for cheaper and return=
 them to you to close out the loan.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Why did you agree to lend the hedge fund the s=
hares, if you knew that the hedge fund was betting they=E2=80=99d go down? =
You=C2=A0<em>own=C2=A0</em>Stock X; you want it to go up; why would you hel=
p someone bet against it? Oh, reasons. You might think =E2=80=9Cthis hedge =
fund is going to short the stock anyway by borrowing it from someone and pa=
ying a fee, so I might as well get the fee.=E2=80=9D You might think =E2=80=
=9Cthis hedge fund thinks the stock will go down, but it is=C2=A0wrong, and=
 I will profit from its folly.=E2=80=9D You might think =E2=80=9Cactually t=
his hedge fund isn=E2=80=99t <em>really=C2=A0</em>betting that the stock wi=
ll go down, but doing some sort of market-neutral or options market-making =
or convertible arbitrage strategy, so there is nothing offensive about its =
shorting.=E2=80=9D You might think =E2=80=9CI am actually an index fund pai=
d to track an index, so I don=E2=80=99t much care if my stocks go up or dow=
n, and getting a little stock-lending income can help me offset my expenses=
.=E2=80=9D Doesn=E2=80=99t matter; the point is that you were happy to get =
some stock-lending income by helping a short seller out.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But now you want to sell the stock, and the ni=
ce pension fund is sitting in your office with its bag of cash, and you ope=
n your vault and there is no stock there. There=E2=80=99s a pile of cash (t=
he collateral from the hedge fund),=C2=A0and a little note saying =E2=80=9C=
IOU=C2=A01,000 shares of Stock X.=E2=80=9D And so you turn to the pension f=
und and say =E2=80=9Coh, sorry, I want to sell you this stock, and I <em>ow=
n=C2=A0</em>it, but I don=E2=80=99t<em> have</em> it right now, can we meet=
 back here in a couple of days and I=E2=80=99ll give it to you?=E2=80=9D</p=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And the pension fund says =E2=80=9Cactually th=
at=E2=80=99s fine, no problem. In fact, to tell you the truth, I was hoping=
 you=E2=80=99d say that, because I don=E2=80=99t have any cash in my bag ei=
ther. You see, as a pension fund, I have a fiduciary duty to maximize retur=
ns, and if I just carried around a bunch of $20 bills in a sack I would not=
 be earning any interest. So in fact I invest all my cash in a money-market=
 fund, which pays a fairly risk-free interest rate, and when I need to buy =
stock I take cash out of the money-market fund=C2=A0to get the $20 bills to=
 pay for the stock. Right now all that=E2=80=99s in the bag is a piece of p=
aper with my money-market fund account number on it. Tell you what, though:=
 You go out and find those stock certificates that you own, and I=E2=80=99l=
l go get=C2=A0cash from my money-market fund, and we=E2=80=99ll meet back h=
ere in a couple of days and swap.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so you agree on a=C2=A0<em>trade </em>=E2=
=80=94=C2=A0a size and price, you sell 1,000 shares of Stock X to the pensi=
on fund for $14 per share =E2=80=94=C2=A0and agree to come back in two days=
 to=C2=A0<em>settle=C2=A0</em>the trade, that is, exchange dollars for shar=
es. This is called =E2=80=9CT+2 settlement.=E2=80=9D And then in the interv=
ening two days everyone is busy:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">You call up the hedge fund and say =
=E2=80=9CHi, remember those 1,000 shares of Stock X I loaned you? I need th=
em back. Can you come by my office tomorrow and return them?=E2=80=9D And t=
he hedge fund says =E2=80=9Csure, we agreed to an open-term loan, and I hon=
or my commitments, so I=E2=80=99ll be there tomorrow with your shares.=E2=
=80=9D</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">But remember, the hedge fun=
d=C2=A0<em>sold=C2=A0</em>your shares! It doesn=E2=80=99t=C2=A0<em>have=C2=
=A0</em>them. So it has to go out and find 1,000 shares of Stock X to retur=
n to you. Probably it will call some=C2=A0<em>other=C2=A0</em>investor and =
say =E2=80=9Chey do you have 1,000 shares of Stock X I can borrow,=E2=80=9D=
 negotiate a new loan, and get the 1,000 shares just in time to meet you at=
 your office tomorrow to return them.=C2=A0</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bott=
om: 5px;">But if it=C2=A0<em>can=E2=80=99t </em>find a new loan, in the wor=
st case, it will have to go out and=C2=A0<em>buy back=C2=A0</em>the 1,000 s=
hares so it can return them to you. But this is tricky, because what if=C2=
=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>trade takes two days to settle? Then the hedge fund w=
on=E2=80=99t have the shares in time to return them to you tomorrow!</li>=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Meanwhile, the pension fund goes to it=
s money market fund manager and says =E2=80=9CI need to cash out $14,000 pl=
ease.=E2=80=9D And the money market fund manager gives it $14,000 and cance=
ls some of its shares.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Where does =
the money market fund get the $14,000 from? Well, probably it owns a bunch =
of Treasury bills, and it goes and sells them in the market for cash, and i=
t uses the cash to pay out the pension fund. That trade, too, has to settle=
: The money market fund has to deliver the bills, and the buyer has to deli=
ver the cash.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And then if all goes well, you meet up two day=
s later and exchange the $20 bills for the stock certificates. But it is no=
t=C2=A0<em>unheard of=C2=A0</em>for all not to go well. You=C2=A0<em>might=
=C2=A0</em>show up two days later with no stock certificates and say =E2=80=
=9Clook, I=C2=A0<em>own=C2=A0</em>that stock, I promise I=E2=80=99m=C2=A0<e=
m>good for it</em>, but what happened is that I lent it out to a hedge fund=
, and I recalled it, and they couldn=E2=80=99t find anyone else to borrow i=
t from, so they had to buy it back in, and they=C2=A0<em>did</em>, they bou=
ght the stock from another investor, but the person they bought it from has=
n=E2=80=99t delivered it yet, but she said that she will tomorrow, and the =
hedge fund will run it over to my office as soon as they get it, so I shoul=
d have it by 2 p.m. tomorrow at the latest, so let=E2=80=99s meet up then, =
really sorry for the inconvenience.=E2=80=9D And the pension fund will be a=
nnoyed, but it will also be like =E2=80=9Cyeah that stuff happens in the st=
ock market, so it goes, see you tomorrow.=E2=80=9D This is called a =E2=80=
=9Csettlement fail.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I am being deliberately silly, and obviously i=
n the real modern world of electronic money and electronic stock and electr=
onic trading platforms each of these steps is easier and faster and more au=
tomated than I am making it out to be, but also=C2=A0<em>this is essentiall=
y accurate</em>. <em>Sometimes</em>, you and I will agree on a stock trade =
(on the exchange) in which you have the stock (in a cash brokerage account<=
a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; te=
xt-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-col=
or: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transp=
arent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>) and I have the cash (at my brokerage) and we could in theory, using t=
he magic of computers, swap them more or less instantly. But for lots of in=
vestors, and particularly institutional investors, <a href=3D"https://link.=
mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34507057.283378/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZX=
JnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDktMjgvZ29sZG1hbi1pbnNpZGVyLXRyYWRlc=
i1kaWQtaGlzLWJlc3Q_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDIyODI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFp=
bCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwMjI4JnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25=
leXN0dWZm/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB80c2e2e7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsco=
pe=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration=
: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; =
border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> that won=E2=80=99t be=
 the norm</a>, because it is=C2=A0<em>inefficient: </em>They won=E2=80=99t =
keep cash parked at their broker if they could be earning more interest in =
Treasury bills; they won=E2=80=99t keep stock parked at their broker if the=
y could be earning fees by lending it out. And so =E2=80=94=C2=A0even with =
the magic of computers and so forth =E2=80=94=C2=A0it will take time for th=
em to swap stock for money to settle their trades.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And in recent years=C2=A0US stock trades have =
had T+2 settlement;=C2=A0that is, trades agreed on a Monday settle on a Wed=
nesday. And now the market is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusines=
s.com/click/34507057.283378/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9uZXdzL3ByZXNzLXJlbGV=
hc2UvMjAyMy0yOQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBff79a5c7" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">moving to T+1 se=
ttlement</a>, for various reasons. One reason is the 2021 <a href=3D"https:=
//link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34507057.283378/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmx=
vb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjEtMDEtMjkvcmVkZGl0LXRyYWRlcnMtb2=
4tcm9iaW5ob29kLWFyZS1vbi1ib3RoLXNpZGVzLW9mLWdhbWVzdG9wP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjgyN=
F9NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90=
ZXJtPTI0MDIyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBe21=
a3e68" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;"> GameStop fiasco</a>, and the fact that the longer the settl=
ement cycle is, the more risk there is that someone might default. (If I ag=
ree to meet you in two days to exchange stock for cash, I might disappear i=
n the intervening days.) But I think another reason might be that, when you=
 tell normal people =E2=80=9Cit takes two days to settle a stock trade,=E2=
=80=9D they kind of don=E2=80=99t believe you? Aren=E2=80=99t the stocks on=
 computers? Isn=E2=80=99t the money on computers? Shouldn=E2=80=99t it take=
 roughly no time to exchange stock for money? And the answer is =E2=80=9Cwe=
ll, kind of, but when you think about the need to line up financing, and to=
 recall stock loans, and the chain of settlement issues that you get if the=
 stock borrower needs to buy in shares and settle=C2=A0<em>that=C2=A0</em>t=
rade, actually it can take a while and it=E2=80=99s a little fragile.=E2=80=
=9D That sounds sort of stupid but is also true.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway Bloomberg=E2=80=99s <a href=3D"https://=
link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34507057.283378/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb=
21iZXJnLmNvbS9uZXdzL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDItMjgvaW52ZXN0b3JzLWZhY2UtMzAtYmls=
bGlvbi1jb3N0LWhpdC1hcy11cy1tYXJrZXRzLW1vdmUtdG8tdC0xP2NtcGlkPUJCRDAyMjgyNF9=
NT05FWVNUVUZGJnV0bV9tZWRpdW09ZW1haWwmdXRtX3NvdXJjZT1uZXdzbGV0dGVyJnV0bV90ZX=
JtPTI0MDIyOCZ1dG1fY2FtcGFpZ249bW9uZXlzdHVmZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBa3138=
f43" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;"> Katherine Doherty reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">US regulators=E2=80=99 plan to speed up settle=
ment times in securities markets will come at a cost for investors around t=
he world =E2=80=94 more than $30 billion annually, according to a new repor=
t from Bloomberg Intelligence.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Settling trades in one day instead of two =E2=
=80=94 under a system dubbed T+1 =E2=80=94 will strain the business of loan=
ing and recalling shares used for short selling, require financing to ensur=
e deadlines can be met and, along the way, risk telegraphing pending stock =
sales to people betting prices will fall, the researchers found.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The resulting impact could amount to about $24=
 billion in securities lending costs, their report estimated. Investors in =
foreign-exchange markets could also face $6.2 billion in added costs.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThe shorter settlement cycle pushes c=
entralized costs, which the banks and the clearinghouses are now managing, =
onto institutional investors,=E2=80=9D Larry Tabb, head of market structure=
 research at Bloomberg Intelligence, said in an interview. =E2=80=9CIt=E2=
=80=99s also leaking a lot of information to folks who borrowed securities =
as well as increasing operational pressure just to execute a trade.=E2=80=
=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">If you are a Bloomberg user, the report, by Ta=
bb and Nicholas Phillips,=C2=A0<a href=3D"bbg://news/stories/S9K216DWLU68" =
itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"c=
olor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; =
border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color:=
 #ccc;">is here</a>. The biggest hit is from recalling stock loans; from th=
e report:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The change in the settlement cycle=
 will necessitate behavioral change in lenders, borrowers, custodians, brok=
er dealers and service providers, because security lenders will have less t=
ime to recall securities on loan and borrowers less time to return them to =
settle a sale of loaned securities. Lenders will be required to recall loan=
s by 11:59 p.m. on the trade date from 3:00 p.m. the day after trading, a r=
eduction of 15 hours to ensure efficient return of stocks, which will be si=
gnificantly less for European and Asian participants.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The window is so narrow that Phillips and Tabb=
 argue=C2=A0that lenders will have to recall stock loans=C2=A0<em>before=C2=
=A0</em>selling the stock: In my example, if you are a mutual fund looking =
to sell Stock X, and you know that you=E2=80=99ll need to deliver it to the=
 buyer as soon as you agree on a trade, then you will=C2=A0<em>first=C2=A0<=
/em>call up the hedge fund that you loaned it to, demand that they return t=
he stock to you, wait until they do, and only=C2=A0<em>then=C2=A0</em>go ou=
t and try to find a buyer. That does solve most of the problems I laid out =
above: If the stock is in your vault before you trade, you don=E2=80=99t ha=
ve to worry about getting it back between trade and settlement. But it is a=
 bit inefficient =E2=80=94=C2=A0there=E2=80=99s some period in which you ow=
n the stock but are not earning fees from lending it out =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=
 also has the problem that the hedge fund might get ideas:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Speeding up the recall process cou=
ld cost investors $17 billion a year in information leakage, we believe. Re=
calling securities before they're sold increases leakage by not only inform=
ing custodians that investors are preparing to sell, but also giving notice=
 to the borrowers, who are already short the issue. Investors who short are=
 typically the most sophisticated, and leaking information to them will onl=
y raise selling pressure and likely have an adverse impact on stock prices.=
</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I don=E2=80=99t think that any of this is=C2=
=A0<em>necessarily=C2=A0</em>true; you probably=C2=A0<em>could=C2=A0</em>bu=
ild a fast-moving electronic marketplace=C2=A0in which stock loans can reli=
ably be recalled (and replaced!) in the space of an hour, so that an asset =
owner could agree to sell stock, recall its stock loan, get the stock back =
and deliver it for settlement a day later. Magic of computers, etc. But tha=
t doesn=E2=80=99t mean that that system currently exists: The current syste=
m is optimized for T+2 settlement, and moving to T+1 will cause some hiccup=
s. And there will always be=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>delay, because stock se=
ttlement is not purely about moving entries around in computer databases. T=
here are actual business decisions that need to be made between the time yo=
u agree on a trade and the time you settle it, and they do take time.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/34507057.283378/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhdy5jb2=
0vYmFua2luZy1sYXcvc29jaWV0ZS1nZW5lcmFsZS1leHRlbmRzLW5pZ2h0LXNoaWZ0LXRvLWhhb=
mRsZS1mYXN0ZXItdXMtdHJhZGluZw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9d50a94e" itemprop=
=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">=
 in Luxembourg</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Societe Generale SA=C2=A0is extending the hour=
s of a night shift team to prepare for the US reducing the time to settle s=
ecurities transactions to just one day.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Luxembourg-based settlement staff in the bank=
=E2=80=99s securities services arm, which has around =E2=82=AC4.9 trillion =
($5.3 trillion) of assets under custody, will work until midnight, from 10 =
p.m. local time previously, according to=C2=A0Mathieu Maurier, who heads th=
e=C2=A0division=E2=80=99s operations in the country. That=E2=80=99s to help=
 ensure trades go through smoothly ahead of the move to so-called=C2=A0T+1.=
</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CMost of the transactions we are getti=
ng from clients are between 10 p.m. and midnight after the closure of the U=
S market,=E2=80=9D he said in an interview. =E2=80=9CWe are anticipating wi=
th T+1 the need to capitalize on those two hours and to handle the pre-matc=
hing element.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Settling trades in a day will keep you busy!</=
p>
