rder-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The meteoric rise of private credit funds has =
been powered by a simple pitch to the insurers and pensions who manage peop=
le=E2=80=99s money over decades: Invest in our loans and avoid the price gy=
rations of rival types of corporate finance. The loans will trade so rarely=
 =E2=80=94 in many cases, never =E2=80=94 that their value will stay steady=
, letting backers enjoy bountiful and stress-free returns. This irresistibl=
e proposal has transformed a Wall Street backwater into a $1.7 trillion mar=
ket.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Now, though, cracks in that edifice are starti=
ng to appear. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0Suddenly, a prime virtue of private credit =E2=
=80=94 letting these funds decide themselves what their loans are worth rat=
her than exposing them to public markets =E2=80=94 is looking like one of i=
ts greatest potential flaws.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Data compiled by Bloomberg and fixed-income sp=
ecialist Solve, as well as conversations with dozens of market participants=
, highlight how some private-fund managers have barely budged on where they=
 =E2=80=9Cmark=E2=80=9D certain loans even as rivals who own the same debt =
have slashed its value. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CIn private markets, because no one kn=
ows the true valuation there=E2=80=99s a tendency to leak information into =
prices slowly,=E2=80=9D says=C2=A0Peter Hecht, managing director at US inve=
stment firm=C2=A0AQR Capital Management. =E2=80=9CIt dampens volatility, gi=
ving this false perception of low risk.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">By the way, in addition to being pleasant for =
the investors, there is=C2=A0<em>some=C2=A0</em>argument that it is sociall=
y useful for=C2=A0<em>lenders=C2=A0</em>not to know what their loans are wo=
rth. We <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34507057.2=
